FAA orders emergency investigation of 2,000 Boeing airliners - Xinhua News Agency
The United States Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) issued an emergency airworthiness directive requiring urgent inspections of approximately 2,000 Boeing 737NG and 737Classic aircraft registered in the United States because the corrosion of the air check valves of these aircraft may cause the engine to stop in the air.
The Federal Aviation Administration stated that it had received four reports of airborne engine parking for 737NG and 737Classic aircraft to date, resulting in urgent inspection requests for airliners that had been parked for seven consecutive days or more and for airliners that had flown fewer than 11 times so far since re-
The Federal Aviation Administration warned that if both engines were corroded, stage 5 check valves could get stuck in the open position, causing the aircraft to lose power completely and fail to restart the engine.
The aviation regulator ordered that once corrosion of the check valve was detected, the airline operator must replace this critical component before the aircraft could be brought back into service.
Boeing responded later that day that the COVID-19 outbreak had reduced demand for travel, resulting in many airliners being blocked or used less frequently, and that "check valves are more susceptible to corrosion."
Boeing meanwhile said it had advised airline operators to inspect airliners covered by the directive and that if problems were found, Boeing would provide help with overhauls and replacement of check valves.
The Associated Press reports that aircraft operated by major U.S. airline operators typically fly multiple times a day, but after the COVID-19 outbreak, a large number of airliners were grounded; some have returned to operations following recent slow growth in passenger demand.
The FAA has not released details of the four air parking reports.
Alaska Airlines 24 later revealed one of the incidents.
The airline said in a statement that one of its airliners was en route from Seattle, Washington, to Austin, Texas, on July 15 when one of its engines stopped and the plane made an emergency landing at Austin Airport.
Alaska Airlines said it had replaced the aircraft's engines and had inspected six of them in accordance with FAA instructions.
American Airlines, United Airlines and Southwest Airlines 24 respectively said that its airliners did not appear associated with air check valve engine stoppage.
Four of American Airlines' airliners will be inspected and 28 of United Airlines' airliners will be inspected.
Delta Air Lines said it would inspect 20 of its airliners, but did not say whether there had been engine outages.
Multiple media reports described the FAA's emergency airworthiness directive as another blow to Boeing.
Lion Air Indonesia and Ethiopian Airlines crashed Boeing 737MAX aircraft in October 2018 and March 2019 respectively, killing 346 people.
The series of airliners was subsequently grounded worldwide, discontinued in January and resumed production in May.
FAA Administrator Steve Dickerson acknowledged in June that the FAA "made mistakes" in regulating Boeing in relation to the 737MAX jetliner.
