Australian University develops new drugs expected to be used to treat coronavirus-induced blood vessel blockage - Xinhua News Agency
Sydney, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Researchers at Monash University in Australia are developing a new drug that could help prevent heart disease and stroke, and hope the drug can be used to treat blood vessel blockages caused by the coronavirus.
Researchers found that an enzyme in platelets accelerates platelet clotting before a heart attack or stroke.
As a result, they developed a drug that temporarily inhibits platelet clotting, thereby avoiding blood vessel blockage and preventing heart attacks and strokes.
Researchers say the drug will only suppress the clotting effect of platelets when there are signs of heart attack or stroke.
With studies showing similar blood vessel blockages are one of the leading causes of death in patients with coronary artery disease, researchers hope the drug could be used in the future to treat patients with such severe conditions.
Currently, the drug has shown good results in animal model experiments, and researchers are preparing for the next phase of human clinical trials.
The research results have been published in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
