France to increase military investment in space
France will add hundreds of millions of euros to its space defense budget and develop military forces in space to guard against "unfriendly moves" that other countries may make in outer space, Defense Minister Florentine Paley said on Tuesday.
Parley told Le Provence newspaper the same day that the spending budget for France's space military programs would increase to 4.3 billion euros ($5 billion) between 2019 and 2025 from a previously proposed 3.6 billion euros ($4.2 billion).
Under the French Military Planning Act 2019-2025 approved by the French Parliament in 2018, France is expected to upgrade its existing observation and communications satellites, launch three electromagnetic listening satellites and modernize its space surveillance radar in the future.
French President Emmanuel Macron announced last July that a military space command and an "air and space force" would be established within the French air force.
Paley said she would make an official announcement about the space force later when she visited a military academy in Salon de Provence.
Parley said the space force is affiliated with the Air Force and has a strength of 500 personnel by 2025.
"Gone is the idea that space served the common good of science; today space is a place where nations compete for global hegemony," she said.
Palley reiterated Macron's previous statement, saying that France has no intention of provoking an arms race.
"We are not in any way engaged in an arms race. But it is my responsibility to be fully aware of the threats we may face."
Palley recalled the surveillance of a French-Italian military satellite in 2017.
What she called a "sneak peek" was a Russian satellite.
The Russian side denies the claim.
France will "soon" have small patrol satellites capable of detecting and targeting "those behind unfriendly moves," Paley said.
According to French media, France sought to create a space force because US President Donald Trump asked the US Department of Defense last February to draft a bill establishing the Space Force.
Trump signed the National Defense Authorization Act last December, authorizing the creation of the United States' sixth largest military force, the Space Force.
Some experts worry that these moves have accelerated the pace of US militarization of space and could trigger a new arms race in space.
