Experts say collecting immigration data through US Census for House seat allocation unconstitutional
Several civil rights groups and several US cities and counties have sued the US federal government, arguing that attempts by the Trump administration to exclude undocumented immigrants from the US census are unworkable and unconstitutional.
The U.S. Census will determine the allocation of seats in the U.S. House of Representatives.
Sarah Brannon, executive counsel for the American Civil Rights Liberties Union, told Voice of America, "It just doesn't work."
She went on to say that Trump's request to determine the citizenship of people who take the census is difficult to do and "not very reliable."
Common Cause, another civil liberties group, filed a lawsuit Thursday challenging Trump's executive order.
Several cities in New Jersey and Georgia joined the lawsuit.
Arlington County, Virginia, also joined the lawsuit Friday.
"The U.S. Constitution requires an accurate count of our population every 10 years... We must accurately count every single person living in Arlington County and cannot allow this illegal attempt to scare people away and compress the size of our immigrant community to succeed," said Garvey, chairman of Arlington County's governing board.
Other organizations and individuals praised President Trump's executive order.
Alabama Attorney General Charles Marshall called the executive order a "victory" for the state.
"The allocation of congressional House seats and Electoral College seats to each state must be based on the number of residents living in the state and who are legally resident," he said.
The U.S. Supreme Court last year blocked the Trump administration from including the citizenship issue in the 2020 census forms.
President Trump signed an executive order earlier this week instructing Commerce Secretary Ross Ross, who oversees the U.S. Census Bureau, to submit census-derived data on undocumented populations so that the administration can exclude them from the census numbers in each state and use that to determine whether each state increases or decreases or maintains House seats.
The United States redistributes House seats every 10 years according to demographic changes.
