Is it reasonable for a 3-year-old child to sue the school after being hit in the college playground?
2020-07-26 05: 01: 11From: Legal Daily Author: Wang Sishuo Responsible Editor: Wang Sishuo
Playground smashed, children sue school after winning compensation
Correspondent Zhao Yifan
Three-year-old Xiaowen was accidentally hit in the head by Chen of the softball team while playing in a college playground.
After Chen compensation, Mr. Wen Xiaowen's father, Mr. Wen Xiaowen, as Xiaowen's legal representative, brought the school to the court, demanding that the school where the playground occurred apologize, and pay medical expenses, moral damage relief and a total of 20,000 yuan.
Recently, Beijing Haidian District People's Court after hearing the case believes that the school set up a protective net in the playground when the incident occurred, has done the appropriate security obligations, and Chen has made compensation, according to which the judgment rejected the plaintiff's claim.
Mr. Wen claims that during the summer vacation of 2019, he took Xiaowen to play in the school playground while the softball team was training in the playground.
In order to avoid this risk, Mr. Xiao Wen, Mr. Wen Wen Wen and many other children and parents operate in the softball team designated safe area.
However, Chen, a member of the softball team, got off his hands while pitching, causing the softball to fly across the net into the above safe area and hit Xiaowen in the back of the
Mr Wen immediately took Xiaowen to hospital for treatment and was diagnosed with head trauma.
According to Mr. Wen, the facilities of the school stadium did not meet the relevant safety regulations and did not effectively manage the team and related facilities.
The fault of the school caused the above incident, which caused Xiaowen to suffer great physical and mental suffering, but also caused greater suffering to his family, for which the school should bear legal responsibility.
In response, the school argued that the school had set up protective nets in the playground and posted regulations and training notices telling it to keep a safe distance from the playground and remind it of its own safety, and that the plaintiffs could not prove that the school had "failed in its safety and security obligations" and therefore did not agree to compensation.
After the hearing, the Court held that the site was open to the public free of charge by the university concerned, and that although the school had a duty of security in relation to the management of the playground, that duty of security was sufficient only to meet the general duty
At the time of the incident, the school set up a protective net in the playground, has done the appropriate security obligations, and Chen also in accordance with the compensation agreement reached earlier to Xiaowen compensation for medical expenses, transportation costs and other losses of more than two thousand yuan, the two sides agreed to
Afterwards, Xiaowen's parents again claimed compensation from the school, and the court decision dismissed all of the plaintiffs' claims.
Following the sentence, neither party appealed and the sentence has now entered into force.
According to Article 37 of China's Tort Liability Law, schools, as managers of public places, have the obligation to ensure safety; in the case of damage caused to others by the acts of third parties, third parties bear tort liability, while public place managers who fail to meet the obligation of security shall bear corresponding supplementary responsibilities.
According to the judge, since, as the administrator of a public place, it is most likely to know the actual situation of the place as a whole, to anticipate the danger and damage that may occur, and thus to take the necessary measures to prevent the occurrence of loss or mitigate the extent of damage, and to avoid and mitigate the damage at the lowest cost, the
In this case, the school's obligation to ensure safety for unspecified persons entering a playground open to the public free of charge should be commensurate with its social activities, in particular basic safety measures and an obligation to inform of hidden dangers.
In judicial practice, it is not appropriate to impose excessive security obligations on managers of public places.
If the school has adopted protective nets and has fulfilled its duty to inform, it can be found that the school is not at fault and should not be held liable.
In addition, in cases of infringement by third parties, the liability of managers of public places such as schools, even if they fail to meet their safety and security obligations, is supplemented by damages. According to the recently enacted Civil Code, managers can also recover compensation from third parties after assuming additional liability.
Therefore, in such accidents, the victim should not extend the scope of his claim after he has received compensation from the direct infringer.
