Yang Hongnian, founder of the Beijing Philharmonic Choir, a famous Chinese conductor and music educator, tenured academic member of the Central Conservatory of Music and professor of conductors, died at 13: 55 on July 26, 2020 in Beijing.
Photo courtesy of Beijing Philharmonic Choir.
Yang Hongnian was born in 1934 in Nanjing, Jiangsu Province.
In 1951 he served as the conductor of the choir of Nanjing People's Radio. In the autumn of 1951 he was admitted to the music department of East China Normal University in Shanghai. He studied conducting under Professor Yang Jiaren and German conductor Hitzman.
In 1958, he taught at the Music Department of Beijing Normal College of Art and in 1973 transferred to the Department of Composition and Conducting of the Central Conservatory of Music.
Yang Hongnian founded the Beijing Philharmonic Choir in 1983.
For more than 30 years, he has led this choir around the world and won dozens of awards in important competitions at home and abroad.
He has conducted more than 30 groups such as Central Orchestra Choir, Central Chinese Song and Dance Company, Oriental Song and Dance Company and Shanghai Choir, and held many symphonic concerts and choral concerts.
His works include "Band Training," "Choral Training," "Two-part Song Writing," "Children's Songbook" (volume) and treatises "On the Choral Intonation Problem," "On the Sound Level Layout of Orchestra," as well as translations of "Choral Orchestrator Law" and "Debussy's Harmonic Language."
