Israel steps up prevention and control of recurrent outbreaks
In the early stages of the COVID-19 outbreak, Israel's prevention and control measures were effective.
However, with the gradual lifting of prevention and control measures, the number of confirmed cases of coronavirus in Israel has recently increased significantly, and the Israeli government has taken several urgent measures to strengthen prevention and control of the epidemic.
On February 28, the first case of coronavirus was confirmed in Israel, which quickly adopted measures such as closing all entry and exit ports, suspending non-essential industries, changing schools to online classes, restricting public transportation and non-essential social activities, blocking cities with severe epidemics, and jointly maintaining prevention and control measures.
These measures quickly yielded positive results, and by mid-May, the number of new confirmed cases of COVID-19 in Israel fell to single digits in a single day.
Since June, the number of new confirmed cases of COVID-19 has gradually rebounded as the outbreak has been brought under control and Israeli prevention and control measures have been fully closed.
Especially since entering July, the spread of the epidemic has accelerated.
In recent days, there have been more than 1,500 new cases per day in Israel for eight days, with 916 new cases as of July 25.
As of 25 July, Israel had 59,745 confirmed cases and 448 deaths.
Faced with the rapid backlash against the outbreak, the Israeli government has repeatedly taken urgent measures to strengthen its prevention and control.
On 6 July, after the number of confirmed cases exceeded 30,000, the Israeli government closed public entertainment venues such as gyms, swimming pools, bars, and nightclubs, and introduced a policy of restricting public transportation to a maximum of 20 passengers per bus.
On May 17, the Israeli government announced a series of new restrictions, including the imposition of "closures" on weekends, between 17: 00 on Fridays and 5: 00 on Sundays.
During this period, people will be able to go outside, but places such as shops, shopping centres, barbershops, beauty salons, libraries, zoos, museums, exhibition halls, swimming pools and tourist attractions will be closed, while places of basic services
Meanwhile, gatherings of more than 10 people will be banned on all dates and times, venues such as gyms and studios will be closed, restaurants and cafes will be banned from eating and only takeaways will be allowed.
At the same time, the Israeli population did not pay enough attention to the seriousness of the epidemic to create synergy with the Government in its fight against it.
Following repeated outbreaks in Israel, many people took to the streets to protest against government control measures affecting their own economic interests.
On 11 July, tens of thousands demonstrated in Tel Aviv, arguing that anti-epidemic policies affected the economy.
On the evening of December 21, thousands more protesters gathered in front of Prime Minister Netanyahu's residence in Jerusalem to protest against measures such as the ban on restaurants and cafs without compensation.
In addition, many people in outdoor activities do not comply with the wearing of masks, maintain a safe social distance of two meters, in order to avoid police fines for not wearing masks, many people only wear masks on the chin or on the wrist.
During the recurrent epidemic, schools are the worst affected areas of the spread of the new coronavirus, and according to the reporter's recent visit to this kindergarten found that teachers and students in kindergartens did not wear masks as required by the government, nor did they maintain a safe social distance of two meters, for a large number of teachers
Professor Elie Waxman, a member of Israel's National Security Council Expert Advisory Panel on Combating the Epidemic, believes that Israel is heading towards a "dangerous situation," pointing out that the current measures taken by Israel to prevent and control the outbreak are insufficient and that all leisure and recreational activities and summer schools
According to Waxman, Israel lacks an overall plan to combat the epidemic, and parliament and government departments should quickly set aside their own interests and reach agreement on combating the epidemic, with clear steps including restrictions on different sectors.
